%I A397258 #13 Jul 07 2026 18:42:36
%S A397258 1,2,3,4,6,7,8,9,12,13,19,20,26,42,43,118,212,220,247,3289
%N A397258 Indices of late birds in Buss's sequence B = A067836: numbers m such that all smaller primes have occurred before B(m).
%C A397258 To tackle Buss's conjecture (cf. A067836), it is useful to know what are the smallest primes that have not yet appeared up to a given point. They are given in A397259, and here we list the indices where they appear.
%C A397258 Indeed, a prime factor of B(n) would have to be distinct from all earlier B(k)'s, but must of course be smaller than B(n) which is smaller than the prime gap at f(n).
%C A397258 It might seem more natural to consider "terms" rather than "primes" in the name. Conjecturally (i.e., if B lists all and only primes), the two are equivalent, i.e., this is the list of m such that B(k) >= B(m) for all k > m (and we know that equality is excluded). But if the conjecture isn't true, we can never know whether a smaller composite number might appear somewhere later in B. With the present definition, we know at once and for sure when a term can be listed.
%e A397258 a(5) = 6 refers to prime B(6) = 11 that appears after B(5) = 13.
%e A397258 a(9) = 12 refers to prime B(12) = 29 that appears not after B(9) = 23 = prime(9), but only after the larger terms B(10) = 37 and B(11) = 73.
%e A397258 a(20) = 3289 refers to where the "long missing" prime 503 = prime(96) finally appears.
%o A397258 (PARI) my(S=[2]); A397258=[k|k<-[1..#A=A067836], !if(A[k]>S[1], S=setunion(S,[A[k]]), until(#S==1||S[2]>S[1]||!S=S[^1],S[1]=nextprime(S[1]+1)))]
%Y A397258 Cf. A067836, A397259 (the "late birds").
%K A397258 nonn,more
%O A397258 1,2
%A A397258 _M. F. Hasler_, Jun 22 2026
